        <h1 class="pg-title">Aphrodite / Venus</h1>
        <p class="pg-subtitle">Greco-Roman goddess of love, beauty, and sexual desire</p>
      </header>

      <p>
        The month of April on the Gregorian calendar honors a goddess of love and sexual desire. The Greeks called her <strong>Aphrodite</strong>; the Romans called her <strong>Venus</strong>. Her worship was ancient, widespread, and deeply tied to ritual prostitution and fertility cults across the Mediterranean world. Most Latin scholars derive the month-name <em>Aprilis</em> from Aphrodite herself — the month opening the season of her festivals.
      </p>

      <h2>Who She Was</h2>

      <p>
        Aphrodite was the Greek goddess of love, beauty, sexual pleasure, and procreation. She had no shame, no boundaries, and no concept of marriage faithfulness in her mythology — her affairs with gods and mortals were a recurring theme in Greek storytelling. She was born, the Greeks said, from sea-foam after the castrated genitals of the sky-god Uranus were thrown into the sea. From her birth forward, every cult site dedicated to her involved practices Yahuah's people would have recognized as abominations.
      </p>

      <p>
        Her temples often featured sacred prostitution. At Corinth, at Cyprus, at Sicilian Eryx, women served as cult prostitutes whose earnings funded the goddess's sanctuary. Worshipers came to lie with these priestesses as an act of devotion. The Romans, when they identified Aphrodite with their own Venus, kept and expanded these practices. Venus was also the supposed ancestor of Julius Caesar's family, who claimed descent from her son Aeneas — which is part of why she became so politically important in Rome.
      </p>

      <p>
        The first of April was historically associated with the <em>Veneralia</em>, a Roman festival in honor of Venus, where women bathed in public baths wearing wreaths of myrtle (her sacred plant) and prayed to her for beauty and success in love. <em>Aprilis</em> — the month — was likely named for Aphrodite because spring was the season of her festivals and the season when love, fertility, and growth came back to the earth.
      </p>

      <h2>Why It Matters</h2>

      <p>
        Yahuah's design for human sexuality is the opposite of everything Aphrodite represented. Marriage covenant, faithfulness, modesty, and self-control — these are the marks of a clean walk before Him. The cult of Aphrodite/Venus was built on the opposite: temple prostitution, ritualized lust, and the celebration of desire as a divine power.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Deuteronomy 23:17–18</span> — "There shall be no whore of the daughters of Israel, nor a sodomite of the sons of Israel. Thou shalt not bring the hire of a whore… into the house of Yahuah thy Elohim for any vow: for even both these are abomination unto Yahuah thy Elohim."
      </div>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">1 Corinthians 6:18–20</span> — "Flee fornication… Know ye not that your body is the temple of the Holy Ghost which is in you… ye are not your own?"
      </div>

      <p>
        Yahuah condemned temple prostitution by name. The very practice that funded Aphrodite's sanctuaries was the practice He explicitly forbade His people from supporting. Naming a month after her — even unintentionally, even by linguistic descent — preserves the name of a goddess whose entire worship system was an abomination to the Father.
      </p>

      <h2>Two Clocks That Cannot Be Mixed</h2>

      <p>
        Some will ask: <em>"What month in Yahuah's calendar is April really?"</em> The question is misplaced.
      </p>

      <p>
        Yahuah's months are counted from the new moon. The first month — Aviv — begins when Spica meets the moon at the new moon nearest the spring equinox. Every month after that begins the day after the visible new-moon sliver appears. The months are numbered. <strong>Their start dates do not line up with the Roman months — and they shift slightly from one year to the next.</strong>
      </p>

      <p>
        What we call "April" on the Roman calendar will overlap with parts of two different months on Yahuah's calendar — and which two depends on the year. To say "April is really Month X" is to commit the same error as saying "Christ died on Friday." It mixes Babylon's clock with Yahuah's clock, when the two were never meant to translate into each other.
      </p>

      <h2>What to Do With It</h2>

      <p>
        The fourth month of the modern calendar carries the name of a goddess whose worship was built on temple prostitution and ritual lust. The springtime feel of "April showers" and "April flowers" is the cultural residue of Aphrodite-worship — the idea that spring belongs to the goddess of beauty and desire. Yahuah owns the spring. The flowers bloom because He sends the rain. The fields awaken because He commands them. No goddess of lust is required to make any of this happen.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Yahuah's clock and Babylon's clock are not the same clock.</strong> His months are counted from the new moon He set in the firmament — not from a Greek goddess of sexual desire. The faithful watch the heavens and let the new moon tell them when a month has begun. The two answers are as far apart as east is from west.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-pull">
        April is Aphrodite's month. The faithful walk in covenant faithfulness, not in the lust she patronized. The heavens know nothing about Venus.
      </div>

